    "body": "Arch Linux\r\n```\r\n$ python --version; cython --version                                      \r\nPython 3.5.2\r\nCython version 0.24.1\r\n\r\n$ cat foo.pyx && cythonize -b foo.pyx && python -c 'import foo'\r\ndef foo(float x=None):\r\n    return x\r\n<elided cythonize output (with no warning)>\r\nTraceback (most recent call last):\r\n  File \"<string>\", line 1, in <module>\r\n  File \"foo.pyx\", line 1, in init foo (/tmp/foo/foo.c:882)\r\n    def foo(float x=None):\r\nTypeError: a float is required\r\n```\r\n\r\nActually, having an error at import time (rather than either compile-time or call-time) is a bit weird (at least from a naive POV).",
